06907nam a2200961Ia 9783110799392DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20242024gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107993927 a10.1515/97831107993922doi  a(DE-B1597)627058  a(OCoLC)1427227111  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aP119.315b.D54 2024 7aLAN0090502bisacsh04a306.449223/eng/2024042400aDigital Flux, Linguistic Justice and Minoritized Languages /ced. by Covadonga Lamar Prieto, Álvaro González Alba. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (VI, 218 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Digital Flux -- tThe (In)visibility of Arabic in Spain: Evidence from Online News Articles -- t“No One Speaks Catalan with Me” — Chinese Learners of Catalan in Barcelona: Difficulties to Learn a Minoritized Language in a Bilingual Society -- t“Náhuat Is Blooming”: Language Revitalization, Recognition and Social Justice -- tBeyond Critical Language Awareness: Reflexivity for Antiracist Critical Literacy in Spanish Language Education -- tIt’s no Coincidence: The Erasure of the Valencian Language in Educational Publishing -- tMultilayered Diglossia: Identity, Ideology, and Linguistic Entropy in Galicia -- tLas realizaciones de /-d/ y /-d-/ en La Pola Siero -- t#Oficialidá: las redes sociales y el impacto glotopolítico en las lenguas minorizadas -- tA Framework for Measuring Language Representation in the Linguistic Landscape: The Case of Los Angeles Koreatown -- tDeveloping Community-Based Sociolinguistic Corpora to Promote Social Justice -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe concept of linguistic justice, as applied to minoritized languages, sheds light upon the way in which minoritized communities conduct their lives in less than optimal environments. Precisely for that reason, the theoretical framework for the study of minoritized languages has been constructed from different areas of knowledge, creating a situation in which "language" is just one of the elements. This collection of essays proposes to recover the centrality of bilingualism, biculturalism and bidialectalism in the understanding of the different social, cultural and political processes of historical and contemporary language justice. It provides relevant theoretical and practical frameworks on the latest studies in linguistic justice as applied to minoritized languages and linguistic varieties such as Korean in Los Angeles, USA, Arabic in Spain, or Náhuat in Central America. Analyzing the acquisition, maintenance and attrition of these languages both in digital and physical environments, the volume contributes to expanding our knowledge of the sociolinguistic, educational, political and social realities that occur in minoritized languages.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aLinguistic minoritiesxSocial conditions. 4aMinderheitensprachen. 4aSpracherhalt/Sprachverfall. 4aZweisprachigkeit. 4asoziale Medien. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Sociolinguistics.2bisacsh  abilingualism.  alanguage maintenance and attrition.  aminoritized languages.  asocial media.1 aAli, Farah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBessett, Ryan M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBleorțu, Cristina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoitel, Quentin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalafate, Isabella, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarvalho, Ana M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/c